If you want to use three or more accounts on the same computer, the easiest and cleanest way to do it is using HTTPS with the username in the URL.

Here is how you do it for any new account:

Method 1: The Easiest Way (Using HTTPS URLs)
When you clone a repository or set a remote URL, add the specific username directly into the URL like this:

bash


git remote set-url origin https://USERNAME@github.com/USERNAME/REPOSITORY.git
For example:

Account 1: https://Satyam123Patel@github.com/Satyam123Patel/repo-one.git
Account 2: https://Satyam1P@github.com/Satyam1P/repo-two.git
Account 3: https://AnotherAccount@github.com/AnotherAccount/repo-three.git
Why this works: Windows Credential Manager is smart. When it sees USERNAME@github.com, it saves a separate login/password (or token) for each username. It will never mix them up.

Method 2: The SSH Way (Using an SSH Config File)
If you prefer SSH for multiple accounts, GitHub doesn't allow you to reuse the same SSH key on different accounts. You must create a new key for each account:

Generate a new key with a unique name (e.g., id_ed25519_third):
powershell


cmd.exe /c "ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -N """" -f C:\Users\Lenovo\.ssh\id_ed25519_third"
Add that key to your third GitHub account.
Create or edit a config file at C:\Users\Lenovo\.ssh\config to map each account:
text


# Account 1 (Satyam123Patel)
Host github.com-main
    HostName github.com
    User git
    IdentityFile ~/.ssh/id_ed25519
# Account 2 (Satyam1P)
Host github.com-second
    HostName github.com
    User git
    IdentityFile ~/.ssh/id_ed25519_second
# Account 3 (ThirdAccount)
Host github.com-third
    HostName github.com
    User git
    IdentityFile ~/.ssh/id_ed25519_third
Update the repository remote URL to use the custom host alias:
bash


git remote set-url origin git@github.com-third:ThirdAccount/repository.git

