1. Generated a New SSH Key
We generated a new, unique SSH key pair (id_ed25519 and id_ed25519.pub) in your computer's C:\Users\Lenovo\.ssh\ folder. This key acts as your computer's secure fingerprint.

2. Created an SSH Config File
We created a configuration file at C:\Users\Lenovo\.ssh\config and added the following instructions to it:

text


Host github.com-second
    HostName github.com
    User git
    IdentityFile C:\Users\Lenovo\.ssh\id_ed25519
This tells Windows: "Whenever a Git URL uses github.com-second, connect to github.com using the SSH key we just generated."

3. Fixed Windows Security Permissions
Windows SSH has a security rule that blocks SSH connections if other users on the computer can read your keys/config. I ran Windows commands (icacls) to lock down the permissions of:

C:\Users\Lenovo\.ssh\config
C:\Users\Lenovo\.ssh\id_ed25519
This ensured only your Windows user (satyam) can read them, which satisfied the SSH security requirements.

4. Pushed Using the Alias URL
Since your repository remote URL was set to: git@github.com-second:Satyam1P/Coding-Notebook.git

Git checked your new SSH config file, used your new SSH key, authenticated you successfully as Satyam1P, and pushed the code!


